                                        <span>Section 5</span>Evolution of the Job Market</h6>
                                </div>
                                <div class="typography-line">
                                    <p>
                                        Separately, I believe understanding the evolution of information technology provides the need to remain competitive in the market. The first era dates back in the mid-1960-1970 when MIS was first computerized. The information systems were centrally located and purely utilized during management. A lot of information was stored in the accounting department and technology mainly encompassed third generation computers, like IBM models.  In the second era, more departments begun to benefit from the MIS, in the mid-1970s until 1980s. The steering head initiated more IS projects. Personal computers and microcomputers were the leading technology.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The third era falls between the mid-1980s and 1990s. The centralized information systems spread out becoming decentralized. Every department had its computers leading to the creation of a new department in the organizations and beginning of internetworking. The fourth era continued in the after 1990 to-date, and information systems are still used in governance. However, the systems are distributed all over the organization to all employees. The main advancement is the MIS has been integrated between the business and its clients so that they can readily access information. Technology lies on social media and other search engines on platforms like smartphones, tablets, and laptops.
